1️⃣ Optional: Remove the Zabbix repository package
sudo apt purge -y zabbix-release
sudo apt update

2️⃣ Verify final cleanup
dpkg -l | grep zabbix
sudo mysql -uroot -p -e "SHOW DATABASES;"

3️⃣ Check Zabbix directories
Look for any leftover config, log, or data directories:
sudo ls -l /etc/zabbix /var/lib/zabbix /var/log/zabbix /usr/share/zabbix

If any exist, they are leftover files.
You can remove them with:
sudo rm -rf /etc/zabbix /var/lib/zabbix /var/log/zabbix /usr/share/zabbix

4️⃣ Check running processes
ps aux | grep zabbix

5️⃣ Optional: Check apt sources
grep -r zabbix /etc/apt/sources.list /etc/apt/sources.list.d/

If you see entries for Zabbix, the repo is still configured.
Remove it with:
sudo apt purge -y zabbix-release
sudo apt update
############REMAINING FILES##############

1️⃣ Check common Zabbix directories
Run:
sudo ls -ld /etc/zabbix /var/lib/zabbix /var/log/zabbix /usr/share/zabbix

If any of these exist, you’ll see a directory listing.
If they don’t exist, you’ll see No such file or directory. ✅

2️⃣ Remove leftover directories (if they exist)
sudo rm -rf /etc/zabbix /var/lib/zabbix /var/log/zabbix /usr/share/zabbix

This deletes all remaining Zabbix configs, data, logs, and frontend files.
Safe because we already removed the database and packages.

3️⃣ Check for stray files elsewhere
sudo find / -iname "*zabbix*" 2>/dev/null

This searches the entire filesystem for any files or folders with “zabbix” in the name.
The 2>/dev/null hides permission errors.
Any entries that appear here are usually safe to delete if you no longer need Zabbix:
sudo rm -rf /path/to/entry
